es their strengths and limits as urban criticism. Contributors explore dystopic images of the modern city in Germany, Mexico, Japan, India, South Africa, China, and the United States. Their topics include Weimar representations of urban dystopia in Fritz Lang's 1927 film Metropolis; 1960s modernist architecture in Mexico City; Hollywood film noir of the 1940s and 1950s; the recurring fictional destruction of Tokyo in postwar Japan's sci-fi doom culture; the urban fringe in Bombay cinema; fictional explorations of urban dystopia in postapartheid Johannesburg; and Delhi's out-of-control and media-saturated urbanism in the 1980s and 1990s. What emerges in Noir Urbanisms is the unsettling and disorienting alchemy between dark representations and the modern urban experience. In addition to the editor, the contributors are David R. Ambaras, James Donald, Rubén Gallo, Anton Kaes, Ranjani Mazumdar, Jennifer Robinson, Mark Shiel, Ravi Sundaram, William M. Tsutsui, and Li Zhang.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCities and towns in motion pictures. 0aCity and town life in motion pictures. 0aFilm noirxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aAmbaras, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonald, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallo, Rubén, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazumdar, Ranjani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrakash, Gyan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrakash, Gyan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobinson, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShiel, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSundar